0.05954093,-0.01975316,0.00332564,-0.0324299,0.16946219,-0.00112496,-0.03510478,0.01821083,-0.03052131,-0.01728811,-0.05638232,0.03091148,0.04714326,0.01039405,0.14543574,-0.00756005,0.06105394,0.02671729,-0.00466468,-0.00296295,-0.0169919,-0.02698147,-0.07155534,0.05675891,-0.07120375,-0.02407324,0.07188512,-0.10772915,-0.0113289,-0.05728149,0.03208752,0.00339323,0.02596097,0.00630166,0.01395902,0.04359096,-0.00085447,-0.00660289,0.07269513,-0.06790059,0.00586285,-0.01611135,0.0113762,-0.02443416,-0.10536554,0.08965184,0.08371073],"last_embed":{"hash":"f20hj2","tokens":451}}},"last_read":{"hash":"f20hj2","at":1774951885296},"class_name":"SmartSource","last_import":{"mtime":1774951813800,"size":5134,"at":1774951884758,"hash":"f20hj2"},"blocks":{"#---frontmatter---":[1,80],"#Antibacterial and anti-coronavirus investigation of selected Senegalese plant species according to an ethnobotanical survey.":[82,86],"#Antibacterial and anti-coronavirus investigation of selected Senegalese plant species according to an ethnobotanical survey.#{1}":[84,86]},"outlinks":[{"title":"Author/A Ba","target":"Author/A Ba","line":63},{"title":"Author/V Roumy","target":"Author/V Roumy","line":64},{"title":"Author/M Ibrahim Al","target":"Author/M Ibrahim Al","line":65},{"title":"Author/I Raczkiewicz","target":"Author/I Raczkiewicz","line":66},{"title":"Author/J Samaillie","target":"Author/J Samaillie","line":67},{"title":"Author/A Hakem","target":"Author/A Hakem","line":68},{"title":"Author/S Sahpaz","target":"Author/S Sahpaz","line":69},{"title":"Author/S Belouzard","target":"Author/S Belouzard","line":70},{"title":"Author/W Diatta","target":"Author/W Diatta","line":71},{"title":"Author/M Sidybé","target":"Author/M Sidybé","line":72},{"title":"Author/C Neut","target":"Author/C Neut","line":73},{"title":"Author/K Séron","target":"Author/K Séron","line":74},{"title":"Author/M Seck","target":"Author/M Seck","line":75},{"title":"Author/C Rivière","target":"Author/C Rivière","line":76}],"metadata":{"id":"a_ba_antibacterial_2024","type":"article-journal","title":"Antibacterial and anti-coronavirus investigation of selected Senegalese plant species according to an ethnobotanical survey.","issued":{"date-parts":[[2024]]},"DOI":"10.1016/j.jep.2024.118070","container-title":"Journal of ethnopharmacology","abstract":"In Senegal, upper and lower respiratory tract infections constitute a real health problem. To manage these disorders, most people rely on the use of local medicinal plants. This is particularly the case for species belonging to the botanical families, Combretaceae, Fabaceae, Myrtaceae and Rubiaceae, which are widely used to treat various respiratory problems such as colds, flu, rhinitis, sinusitis, otitis, angina, bronchitis, bronchiolitis and also pneumonia.The aim of this study was to identify medicinal plants traditionally used for the management of infectious diseases, in particular those of the respiratory tract. On the basis of these ethnopharmacological uses, this study made it possible to highlight the antibacterial, antiviral and cytotoxic activities of selected plant species.An ethnobotanical survey was conducted in Senegal among informants, including herbalists, traditional healers, and households, using medicinal plants in the management of infectious diseases, with a focus on respiratory tract infections. The most cited plant species were evaluated in vitro on a panel of 18 human pathogenic bacteria may be involved in respiratory infections and against the human coronavirus HCoV-229E in Huh-7 cells. The antiviral activity of the most active extracts against HCoV-229E was also evaluated on COVID-19 causing agent, SARS-CoV-2 in Vero-81 cells. In parallel, cytotoxic activities were evaluated on Huh-7 cells.A total of 127 informants, including 100 men (78.74%) and 27 women (21.26%) participated in this study. The ethnobotanical survey led to the inventory of 41 plant species belonging to 19 botanical families used by herbalists and/or traditional healers and some households to treat infectious diseases, with a specific focus on upper respiratory tract disorders. Among the 41 plant species, the most frequently mentioned in the survey were Guiera senegalensis J.F. Gmel. (95.2%), Combretum glutinosum Perr. Ex DC. (93.9%) and Eucalyptus spp. (82.8%). Combretaceae (30.2%) represented the most cited botanical family with six species, followed by Fabaceae (29.3%, 12 species). A total of 33 crude methanolic extracts of the 24 plant species selected for their number of citations were evaluated in vitro for their antimicrobial and cytotoxic activities. Guiera senegalensis, Combretum glutinosum, Vachellia nilotica subsp. tomentosa (Benth.) Kyal. & Boatwr, Eucalyptus camaldulensis Dehnh., and Terminalia avicennioides Guill. & Perr., showed antibacterial activities. The most active plants against HCoV-229E were: Ficus sycomorus L., Mitragyna inermis (Willd.) Kuntze, Pterocarpus erinaceus Poir., and Spermacoce verticillata L. One of these plants, Mitragyna inermis, was also active against SARS-CoV-2.This work confirmed the anti-infective properties of plant species traditionally used in Senegal. Overall, the most frequently cited plant species showed the best antibacterial activities. Moreover, some of the selected plant species could be considered as a potential source for the management of coronavirus infections. This new scientific data justified the use of these plants in the management of some infectious pathologies, especially those of the respiratory tract.Copyright © 2024 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","tags":["#literature_note"],"author":[{"family":"A Ba","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"V Roumy","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"M Ibrahim Al","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"I Raczkiewicz","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"J Samaillie","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"A Hakem","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"S Sahpaz","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"S Belouzard","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"W Diatta","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"M Sidybé","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"C Neut","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"K Séron","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"M Seck","given":"","literal":""},{"family":"C Rivière","given":"","literal":""}],"citation-key":"a_ba_antibacterial_2024","year":"2024","dateCreated":"2026-03-31","reading-status":"to-read","aliases":["Antibacterial and anti-coronavirus investigation of selected Senegalese plant species according to an ethnobotanical survey."],"author-links":["[[Author/A Ba]]","[[Author/V Roumy]]","[[Author/M Ibrahim Al]]","[[Author/I Raczkiewicz]]","[[Author/J Samaillie]]","[[Author/A Hakem]]","[[Author/S Sahpaz]]","[[Author/S Belouzard]]","[[Author/W Diatta]]","[[Author/M Sidybé]]","[[Author/C Neut]]","[[Author/K Séron]]","[[Author/M Seck]]","[[Author/C Rivière]]"],"attachment":[],"related":[[]]},"task_lines":[],"tasks":{},"codeblock_ranges":[],"last_embed":{"hash":"f20hj2","at":1774951885286}},"smart_blocks:Research/@a_ba_antibacterial_2024.md#---frontmatter---": {"path":null,"embeddings":{"TaylorAI/bge-micro-v2":{"vec":[-0.013296,0.019573,0.00885627,0.02050295,0.09743711,-0.05836103,0.057045,0.05446627,-0.02968364,0.02984175,-0.01270814,-0.09347527,0.00544288,0.0356355,-0.00903596,0.00608153,-0.00335676,-0.01690225,-0.05816659,-0.00562112,-0.0368241,0.0172797,0.02288652,-0.03421342,0.01836559,0.02778465,0.02019256,-0.01279084,-0.06031012,-0.15718471,-0.01431489,0.0139611,0.02571463,-0.00013584,-0.03795535,0.01364466,-0.02819253,0.04575241,-0.02743701,0.03917831,0.01872811,0.00628711,0.02073106,-0.02602895,-0.04374282,-0.02777752,-0.08016423,-0.01641556,0.02458674,-0.08319631,-0.01987077,-0.07414383,0.03516446,0.01501108,-0.02223487,-0.02368256,0.06047126,-0.0013609,-0.08609898,0.05680014,0.14181401,0.00955312,-0.23049256,0.06210295,-0.01144415,0.00261714,-0.0171964,-0.03852882,0.10024849,0.01079839,-0.09787232,-0.01072626,-0.04236742,0.01091124,0.01644629,-0.00778202,-0.03356258,-0